{"source_key":"sha256-ea08d35f42d5530fbe92c80d4f5b27e9","record_index":1029,"record_hash":"sha256:27924c4803a1ce5c51f786c5f03d9eaa57a0cf8df60a4dce6c81cb826ff43bb9","timestamp":"2026-05-24T16:18:00.722Z","kind":"tool_call","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:custom_tool_call","role":null,"text":null,"tool_name":"apply_patch","tool_input":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Update File: agent-trail.md\n@@\n-## Node/Rust Boundary\n-\n-After online runtime research, the preferred production boundary is:\n-\n-```text\n-Agent Trail web/API facade -> Agent Trail generator service -> but-agentlog projection API\n-```\n-\n-In that shape the generator can be a small Rust HTTP worker and does not need\n-NAPI. Use NAPI only if the generator is intentionally embedded in a Node web\n-process.\n-\n-GitButler already has a working NAPI pattern:\n-\n-- `crates/but-api` marks Rust APIs with `#[but_api(napi)]`\n-- `crates/but-napi` is a `cdylib` that links the generated exports\n-- `packages/but-sdk` runs `@napi-rs/cli`, ships generated `index.js`,\n-  `index.d.ts`, and platform `.node` artifacts, and exposes typed functions to\n-  Electron's main process\n-\n-Agent Trail should borrow the packaging shape, not the whole desktop API\n-surface. Do not make the hosted product depend on the broad\n-`@gitbutler/but-sdk` package just to read agent logs; it brings unrelated\n-workspace, mutation, legacy, and desktop concepts into a server feature that\n-should stay narrow.\n-\n-The conditional in-process Node boundary is:\n-\n-```text\n-Node web/API handler -> TypeScript AgentTrail service -> dedicated Agent Trail NAPI package\n-```\n-\n-Use this only if the web/API runtime is confirmed to support the local\n-repository cache and native addon requirements. Put the native package in the\n-GitButler repository, next to `but-agentlog`, not inside the hosted product. That\n-keeps the Rust dependency graph and storage interpretation with the code that\n-owns it. The hosted product should consume the generated npm package.\n-\n-Good GitButler-side package shape:\n-\n-```text\n-crates/but-agenttrail-napi\n-packages/but-agenttrail-sdk\n-```\n-\n-The native package should expose one small server-only function first:\n-\n-```text\n-projectAgentTrail(request: AgentTrailProjectionRequest) -> AgentTrailProjection\n-```\n-\n-The request should contain the prepared repo path or GitMeta source, resolved\n-metadata OID, PR facts, limits, and projection version. The response should be\n-only the public Agent Trail projection. The native layer should not perform\n-GitHub HTTP, own snapshot retention, render UI, or know about hosted-product\n-sessions.\n-\n-Use the existing `but-api`/`but-sdk` macro pipeline only if it fits naturally.\n-Agent Trail does not have the usual GitButler desktop `projectId -> Context`\n-shape, so a direct `napi-rs` function may be cleaner than forcing it through\n-`but-api`. The important part is the generated typed Node package and native\n-artifact workflow, not reuse of the entire `but-api` surface.\n-\n-Minimum implementation shape:\n-\n-```text\n-gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog\n-  src/agent_trail.rs            # public projection API and DTOs\n-\n-gitbutler/crates/but-agenttrail-napi\n-  Cargo.toml                    # cdylib, depends on but-agentlog + napi-rs\n-  build.rs                      # napi_build::setup()\n-  src/lib.rs                    # #[napi] project_agent_trail(...)\n-\n-gitbutler/packages/but-agenttrail-sdk\n-  package.json                  # @napi-rs/cli build scripts\n-  src/generated/index.js\n-  src/generated/index.d.ts\n-  src/generated/*.node\n-```\n-\n-The generated npm package should be server-only. It should not ship browser\n-behavior beyond a stub that throws clearly if imported client-side.\n-\n-Initial package scripts can mirror `packages/but-sdk`:\n-\n-```json\n-{\n-  \"scripts\": {\n-    \"build:napi\": \"napi build --platform --esm --manifest-path ../../crates/but-agenttrail-napi/Cargo.toml --js index.js --dts index.d.ts --output-dir ./src/generated/.\",\n-    \"build:napi:release\": \"napi build --platform --release --esm --manifest-path ../../crates/but-agenttrail-napi/Cargo.toml --js index.js --dts index.d.ts --output-dir ./src/generated/.\",\n-    \"check\": \"tsc -p tsconfig.generated.json --noEmit\"\n-  },\n-  \"napi\": {\n-    \"binaryName\": \"gitbutler-agenttrail\",\n-    \"targets\": [\n-      \"x86_64-apple-darwin\",\n-      \"aarch64-apple-darwin\",\n-      \"x86_64-unknown-linux-gnu\"\n-    ]\n-  }\n-}\n-```\n-\n-Add Windows only if there is a real deployment or developer need for it.\n-Linux musl should be an explicit decision, not accidental scope.\n-\n-The first Rust NAPI wrapper can be intentionally boring:\n-\n-```rust\n-#[napi]\n-pub async fn project_agent_trail(\n-    request: serde_json::Value,\n-) -> napi::Result<serde_json::Value>\n-```\n-\n-That keeps the NAPI boundary stable while the projection DTOs are still moving.\n-Once the projection settles, replace raw `serde_json::Value` with generated\n-typed DTOs or a schema-driven `.d.ts` append step like `but-ts`.\n-\n-The request should include:\n-\n-- `repoPath` or a future explicit GitMeta source handle\n-- `metadataOid`\n-- `pr`: Agent Trail host, GitHub repo id, owner, repo, PR number, base ref,\n-  head ref, and head SHA\n-- `limits`: max sessions, turns, records, bytes per record, total bytes, and\n-  runtime deadline\n-- `projectionVersion`\n-\n-The response should include only the public projection and status/warning\n-fields. It must not include raw session keys, raw turn keys, provider session\n-ids, filesystem paths, `source_record`, or hidden/system/developer messages.\n-\n-If the generator is embedded in a TypeScript web app, consumption should stay\n-behind server-only modules:\n-\n-```text\n-agent-trail/native adapter      # imports @gitbutler/but-agenttrail-sdk\n-agent-trail/service layer       # GitHub lookup, cache, fetch, snapshot flow\n-agent-trail API handler         # JSON API route\n-agent-trail page handler        # page over the API/projection\n-```\n-\n-Local development can depend on the generated package by path after building it\n-in the GitButler checkout:\n-\n-```json\n-\"@gitbutler/but-agenttrail-sdk\": \"file:../gitbutler/packages/but-agenttrail-sdk\"\n-```\n-\n-Production should use a pinned package artifact or private package release,\n-not an implicit local checkout. The package version or artifact digest should\n-be part of the Agent Trail deployment input so the web/API layer and Rust\n-projection version move together intentionally.\n-\n-All routes that touch the native package should set `runtime = 'nodejs'` and\n-must not be imported by client components. If Next's bundler tries to package\n-the native module incorrectly, configure the SDK as a server-side external\n-package rather than importing generated `.node` artifacts directly.\n-\n-The helper-binary fallback remains valid when deployment constraints make NAPI\n-awkward:\n-\n-```text\n-Node web/API handler -> TypeScript AgentTrail service -> Rust projection helper JSON\n-```\n-\n-Use that only as an in-process Node fallback. NAPI avoids a custom\n-stdout/stderr protocol, process spawning, and binary lifecycle management inside\n-each request. A separate Rust generator service avoids both NAPI and helper\n-binary packaging in the web/API layer.\n+## Runtime Boundary\n+\n+Do not make this a microservice system for v1. Use a modular monolith: one\n+repository, one deployable service, one mounted volume, clean internal modules.\n+\n+Preferred production boundary:\n+\n+```text\n+Agent Trail app\n+  HTTP routes / API / page rendering\n+  GitHub public PR lookup\n+  internal generation module\n+  local repository cache\n+  but-agentlog projection API\n+```\n+\n+The cleanest v1 implementation is a small Rust web app, likely Axum or similar,\n+that links the `but-agentlog` public/read projection API directly. That avoids\n+NAPI, helper binaries, and service-to-service HTTP. It also keeps the filesystem\n+work in the same runtime that owns the volume.\n+\n+The internal generation function should be boring:\n+\n+```text\n+generate_agent_trail(request: AgentTrailProjectionRequest)\n+  -> AgentTrailProjectionResult\n+```\n+\n+The request should include:\n+\n+- `repoPath` or a future explicit GitMeta source handle\n+- `metadataOid`\n+- `pr`: Agent Trail host, GitHub repo id, owner, repo, PR number, base ref,\n+  head ref, and head SHA\n+- `limits`: max sessions, turns, records, bytes per record, total bytes, and\n+  runtime deadline\n+- `projectionVersion`\n+\n+The response should include only the public projection and status/warning\n+fields. It must not include raw session keys, raw turn keys, provider session\n+ids, filesystem paths, `source_record`, or hidden/system/developer messages.\n+\n+If the project later chooses a Node/Next monolith for web ergonomics, then use\n+GitButler's NAPI pattern with a dedicated Agent Trail package. GitButler already\n+has a working NAPI shape:\n+\n+- `crates/but-api` marks Rust APIs with `#[but_api(napi)]`\n+- `crates/but-napi` is a `cdylib` that links the generated exports\n+- `packages/but-sdk` runs `@napi-rs/cli`, ships generated `index.js`,\n+  `index.d.ts`, and platform `.node` artifacts\n+\n+In that case, borrow the packaging pattern, not the broad desktop API surface.\n+Do not make Agent Trail depend on the full `@gitbutler/but-sdk` just to read\n+agent logs.\n+\n+Conditional Node package shape:\n+\n+```text\n+gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog\n+  src/agent_trail.rs            # public projection API and DTOs\n+\n+gitbutler/crates/but-agenttrail-napi\n+  Cargo.toml                    # cdylib, depends on but-agentlog + napi-rs\n+  src/lib.rs                    # #[napi] project_agent_trail(...)\n+\n[REDACTED:entropy]\n+  package.json                  # @napi-rs/cli build scripts\n+  src/generated/index.js\n+  src/generated/index.d.ts\n+  src/generated/*.node\n+```\n+\n+A helper binary is the fallback only if a TypeScript/Node monolith is chosen and\n+NAPI packaging becomes painful. It should not be the default architecture.\n*** End Patch\n","source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-24T16:18:00.722Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"custom_tool_call","status":"completed","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]","name":"apply_patch"}}}